If you are iffy, hesitant, unsure, about trans athletes- PLEASE give this short video a chance.

First of all, thank you @pinkmantaray for the time, energy, and emotional labor you dedicate to this cause every single day. It is not the responsibility of the trans community to educate others, yet you patiently & enthusiastically do. I am incredibly grateful for your participation in this interview and for everything that you put out on a daily basis!!!

Secondly, @realpod, in it’s most simple form, is about being candid and getting real. While I am embarrassed by my own ignorance (🙃) I hope Schuyler‘s answer (and our entire one hour conversation!!) can be the difference that helps garner more support for transgender athletes. I am eager to passionately and loudly help fight for these players.

Schuyler was the first openly transgender D1 NCAA athlete and swam at Harvard. (Yep, HARVARD!) His knowledge is BEYOND and in this podcast episode he proceeds to TAKE 👏 US 👏 TO 👏 CHURCH 👏 about all things gender identity, transitioning, and transgender rights. Please do take the time to listen to our full 45 minute conversation at the Real Pod link in my bio. 

And follow him at @pinkmantaray - PLS!

After passionately sharing my support for both Simone Biles' and Naomi Osaka's choices regarding their mental health, I've been asked "what my story is" and "why I care so much." 

Well, before all of this, I was an athlete. I l played at the DI level for the USC Women's Volleyball Team, a childhood dream of mine.

It was there, living my dream, that I felt the most alone, the most afraid, and the most at war with myself. (I want to note that this had nothing to do with USC, I love that school.) This was because of the unrelenting pressure, impossible standard, and high-pressure environment that elite athletes live in. This was something I did not feel prepared for, and as a result did not know how to handle. I began battling performance anxiety, fell into a major depressive episode, & developed a binge-eating disorder.

Through my mental health battle, I was exposed to the powerful stigma that belittles mental health issues. It's a stigma that says you're weak for seeking help and soft for not being able to take it. It's a stigma that says "there's something wrong with you," because you couldn't hang like everyone else. It's a stigma that convinces those around you to view you as difficult and sensitive. And better yet, it's a stigma that loves joining forces with toxic sports culture. (Those are the people society views as the strongest! Those are the people who never want to show a sign of weakness!)

Once I realized what I was going through - a universal experience that happens to many people everyday - I grew deeply passionate about rewriting the narrative around mental health, especially in sports. Today, I am re-sharing my TEDxTalk from 2017. This was the first time I ever spoke publicly about my issues - desperate for people to understand. Thank you in advance to anyone who takes the time to watch it. 

Simone Biles & Naomi Osaka compete at a level that's 100X more intense, severe, and pressure inducing than the one I played on. THAT is why what they are doing is so important. 🙏

- Why is this a big deal?
- Why didn’t college athletes have this right before? 
- What exactly is someone’s NIL?? 
- Does this go for every division?
- How can I make money if I’m a college athlete?? 💰💰💰 
- My #1 tip for growth on social media 
AND MORE…

Link in my bio to watch :)

PS: College athletes… if I hosted a webinar to share inside information on how to build a brand, leverage your social media platforms, and monetize yourself would you be interested?! Comment a “🙌” if so… cuz I’m thinking about it!

If you’re trying to navigate this with your S/O, I have two tips from my experience...

1) The first thing you need to do is assess what YOU need. Using myself as an example, I need a partner who won’t judge me or make comments about my food choices/eating habits. Knowing I am free from that makes me feel so safe in listening to my body and making my own choices.

2) Now that you know what you need, COMMUNICATE that to your partner in the best way possible. Hopefully you are with someone who wants to honor your wishes so that they can support you.

@maxbrowne thanks for all that you do to support me and my 🧠!! I love you! 

PS: This clip is from my interview on my good friend @katieaustin YT show!! It was SO fun and I loved our conversation. Please check it out on Austin AF YouTube Channel + link is on my stories :)

It was an honor to sit down with one of the most historic and badass female athletes of our generation for an interview on @realpod!!! 

Sarah made history as the first woman to play football AND score a point in a Power Five game. On this episode she shares details of who she was before the world knew her name, the phone call that changed her life, and how she handled all the resulting comments and fame from hundreds of thousands around the country who watched.

LINK IN BIO TO LISTEN TO THIS EPISODE!! Thank you @sarah_f27 you are the best! Rooting for you on and off both fields ✌️💓

In 2018, @playerstribune and I teamed up to address body-image issues amongst female athletes. I was joined by these incredible USC athletes who bravely opened up about the many issues female athletes face when it comes to body-image and eating disorders. (According to @neda over 1/3 of female college athletes reported symptoms of an eating disorder.)

For #NationalWomenInSportsDay I wanted to re-share this video to remind the many incredible, strong, accomplished female athletes out there that you’re not alone in your body-image struggles. (And to the men and non-binary athletes! I see you!!! ❤️)

Always remember, your body is not an ornament... it’s and instrument!! 🙌

YT Link: https://youtu.be/ZCqB1dUUOoI

Thanks again to these studs: @mcrightsideoflife @its_ambers_world @hannileach
@sarahmarielivi @oliviaontjes @chloechrysikopoulos @pippppppper

Whether it’s a teammate who feels the need to tell everyone about their new diet, a friend who constantly makes you self-conscious about what you eat, or that family member who obsesses over YOUR appearance, (🤦🏼‍♀️) we need to know how to react and protect ourselves in these situations.

Thank you Elyse Resch for describing 4 great ways we can navigate these tough encounters with family and friends this holiday season. My personal favorite is to communicate... y’all I know I love me some healthy confrontation! ☺️😂 Which tip works best for you? Let me know I’d love to hear!⬇️

Our full one hour conversation of @realpod titled, “How To Intuitively Eat on Thanksgiving & Navigate Food Around The Holidays” is available to stream on all podcast platforms! Check it out if you haven’t yet!

First of all, thank you @pinkmantaray for the time, energy, and emotional labor you dedicate to this cause every single day. It is not the responsibility of the trans community to educate others, yet you patiently & enthusiastically do. I am incredibly grateful for your participation in this interview and for everything that you put out on a daily basis!!!

Secondly, @realpod, in it’s most simple form, is about being candid and getting real. While I am embarrassed by my own ignorance (🙃) I hope Schuyler‘s answer (and our entire one hour conversation!!) can be the difference that helps garner more support for transgender athletes. I am eager to passionately and loudly help fight for these players.

Schuyler was the first openly transgender D1 NCAA athlete and swam at Harvard. (Yep, HARVARD!) His knowledge is BEYOND and in this podcast episode he proceeds to TAKE 👏 US 👏 TO 👏 CHURCH 👏 about all things gender identity, transitioning, and transgender rights. Please do take the time to listen to our full 45 minute conversation at the Real Pod link in my bio. 

And follow him at @pinkmantaray - PLS!

node.text:
isn’t it crazy how one moment you can feel great about your body, and then the next day you can feel crummy?? I feel like I’ve up and down almost every day this week…

Goes to show that our feelings for our body itself are ever changing... We’re never going to ALWAYS love our bodies 24/7, that’s just the reality of it. (Being 100% happy with anything all the time is impossible!) 

And I think it’s important to acknowledge that so that when the down days come we don’t get even more upset with ourselves for having a down day.. ya know?! Because they are inevitable.

So if today’s not your day, I see you.
If it is, I see you.

Either way…

It’s just a day, and it’s just a body. 🤷🏼‍♀️🤍 #RealPost

Is anyone else being personally victimized by their period right now? (ya, we get right into it on this page 🙃 #RealPost - also, so many people get their period so YES, we are going to talk about it!) #ad 

I used to find myself in these frustrating mental ruts every month where I just wasn't feeling like my best self. I also would get this random, yet excruciating, back pain and I had no idea where it was coming from! Thanks to a lot of you helping me connect the dots, I was able to realize these things all happen in the days leading up to my period. As silly as it sounds, I never even thought to think of that connection before... and I feel like I’m just finally beginning to understand my period!! (and I’m 24!!) Now, I’m determined to learn more about what’s going on so I can figure out what’s best for me and my body, especially since the moodiness and back pain have been so persistent and disruptive to my daily life. 

I have an appointment with a new OBGYN coming up, am getting a hormone panel test, and have been trying to educate myself on all things period from some great IG accounts. In the meantime, BIG shoutout to @advilrelief for helping me relieve my back pains and aches. Backaches are by far my worst period symptom, so taking Advil has really helped make it more bearable. (PS: Advil is my go to for pain relief, even as an athlete - the Garricks are an Advil family! 😅) 

Will keep you all posted on my ✨period journey✨as I continue to learn more.

PS: If you’re on the same cycle as me, comment a “ 🙌” We're in this together, SQUAD UP! 

#strivehealth @strive.health

🚨 Four quick pieces of back to school advice!! 

1️⃣ If you’re feeling totally stressed & overwhelmed like the water is just slowly rising all around you… that’s normal! :) Just a few months ago you were bored out of your mind on Zoom, had no practice, no in person requirements, and now it’s like you’ve been thrust back into life at 2x speed. Starting a new school year always has challenges, especially this one. Please don’t feel like there’s something wrong with you if you’ve been having a hard time adjusting - THIS IS HARD.

2️⃣ The next few weeks will not make or break your life. While it can FEEL like if we don’t earn a starting spot, don’t get into the class we want, don’t get into the house of our choice, etc, that your life’s going to end… I promise, it’s not. People say ‘life is short’ so much that we forget life is also LONGGG. Take a deep breath, trust the process. There’s opportunity and growth in the setbacks. One day you will look back and see how the dots connected.

3️⃣ Everyone is going through something! Whether it’s big or little, nobody is as happy or perfect as it might seem. (I just had the engagement of my dreams but I was crying earlier today - why?! Cuz I’m human and I got sad about something.) Every person you come into contact with is a human being who has cried themselves to sleep, who has their own struggles, and who just wants to be liked and loved too. Remember this when you’re tempted to compare your Fall to someone else’s… 

4️⃣ Let people in. You are not a burden. Your feelings - whatever they may be right now - are valid. 🤍

Drop a “❤️” if this was helpful! Love you guys. You got this! 💪

👏 YOU ARE SO MUCH MORE THAN YOUR GRAVITATIONAL PULL TO THE EARTH 👏

(See!? Doesn’t that sound silly?! We’re all trying to lower our gravitational pull to the earth… For WHAT!? 😂)

My relationship with the scale was toxic for most of my life… I would literally let it grant me the permission to either love or hate myself that day. (Exhausting!) I realized I needed to make a change, and I haven’t weighed myself in over three years. This was the solution that worked best for me as I was trying to develop a better relationship with my body. 

(Not to mention, I’ve since realized there’s absolutely nothing wrong with weighing more or having a higher weight.)

In general, it’s just been freeing to realize I am more than a number…

and so are YOU! :)
